VALUES
(42, 22, 7, 2, 12, 6, 6, 'when the passover must be killed', 'Connection of Passover Rituals', 'This connection highlights the timing of the Passover sacrifice in both passages. Luke 22:7 refers to the day when the Passover must be killed, paralleling Exodus 12:6, which specifies the assembly killing the lamb in the evening.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 7, 42, 22, 1, 1, NULL, 'Connection of Passover and Unleavened Bread', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of the feast of unleavened bread, which is directly linked to the Passover. The mention of the Passover in both verses highlights its importance in the context of the events described.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 7, 46, 5, 7, 7, 'when the passover must be killed', 'Connection of Passover and Christ', 'This connection highlights the significance of the Passover in both passages. Luke refers to the Passover being killed, while 1 Corinthians identifies Christ as our Passover, emphasizing the sacrificial role of Christ in relation to the Passover feast.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 7, 40, 26, 17, 19, 'the passover must be killed', 'Passover Preparation Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of the Passover and its preparation. Luke mentions the day of unleavened bread, while Matthew details the disciples preparing for the Passover meal.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 8, 41, 14, 13, 16, 'prepare us the passover', 'Preparation for the Passover', 'Both passages emphasize the preparation for the Passover meal. They describe the sending of disciples to make arrangements for this significant event.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 8, 42, 1, 6, 6, NULL, 'Righteousness and Preparation', 'This connection highlights the theme of righteousness in both passages. In Luke 1:6, the emphasis on being blameless before God parallels the preparation for the Passover in Luke 22:8, which is a significant act of obedience to God''s commandments.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 8, 44, 3, 1, 1, 'Peter and John', 'Connection of Peter and John', 'This connection highlights the ongoing partnership of Peter and John in their ministry. Both passages emphasize their collaborative actions, first in preparing for the Passover and later in going to the temple together.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 8, 44, 3, 11, 11, 'Peter and John', 'Connection of Peter and John', 'This connection highlights the ongoing role of Peter and John in the early church. Both passages emphasize their leadership and involvement in significant events, from preparing the Passover to healing the lame man.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 8, 48, 4, 4, 5, 'prepare us the passover', 'Connection of Redemption and Preparation', 'This connection highlights the theme of preparation for redemption. In Luke, the preparation of the Passover signifies the coming of Jesus, who, as stated in Galatians, was sent to redeem those under the law.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 8, 40, 3, 15, 15, NULL, 'Fulfillment of Righteousness', 'This connection highlights the theme of preparation for significant events. In Luke, the preparation for Passover signifies a pivotal moment, while in Matthew, fulfilling righteousness indicates the importance of readiness for divine purposes.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 10, 9, 10, 2, 7, 'a man meet you', 'Meeting Signs in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of encountering specific individuals as signs of divine guidance. In Luke, the man with the pitcher leads to a significant event, paralleling the signs given to Saul in 1 Samuel.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 10, 40, 26, 18, 19, NULL, 'Preparation for the Passover', 'This connection highlights the instructions given to the disciples regarding the preparation for the Passover meal. Both passages emphasize the act of going into the city and following a man to a specific location for this significant event.', 'parallel', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 10, 43, 16, 4, 4, NULL, 'Preparation for Future Events', 'This connection highlights the theme of preparation for future events. In Luke, Jesus instructs his disciples on what to expect, while in John, he reminds them of prior teachings to prepare them for what is to come.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 10, 44, 8, 26, 29, 'follow him into the house', 'Divine Guidance in Both Passages', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine guidance in both passages. In Luke, Jesus instructs his disciples to follow a man, while in Acts, the Spirit directs Philip to approach the eunuch''s chariot.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 10, 42, 19, 29, 40, NULL, 'Preparation for Jesus'' Entry', 'Both passages emphasize the preparation for Jesus'' arrival. In Luke 22:10, the instruction to follow a man with a pitcher signifies a specific preparation, while in Luke 19:29-40, the disciples are sent to find a colt, also indicating a planned entry for Jesus.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 11, 43, 11, 28, 28, 'The Master', 'Connection of ''The Master''', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of ''The Master'' calling for someone. In Luke, ''The Master'' seeks a place to eat, while in John, ''The Master'' calls for Mary, highlighting His authority and relational engagement.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 11, 40, 21, 3, 3, 'The Master saith unto thee', 'Connection of Authority and Need', 'This connection highlights the theme of authority, as both passages involve a directive from the Master or Lord. Each verse emphasizes the necessity of responding to the Master''s request, indicating a shared understanding of obedience and purpose.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 11, 42, 19, 5, 5, NULL, 'Hospitality and Invitation', 'This connection highlights the theme of hospitality, as both passages involve Jesus requesting to stay at someone''s house. In Luke 22:11, Jesus seeks a place to eat the Passover, while in Luke 19:5, he invites himself to Zaccheus'' house.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 11, 42, 19, 31, 31, 'The Master saith unto thee', 'Authority of the Lord', 'Both passages emphasize the authority of the Lord in directing actions. In Luke 22:11, the disciples are instructed to ask about the guest chamber because ''The Master saith unto thee,'' while in Luke 19:31, they are to respond with ''Because the Lord hath need of him.''', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 11, 66, 3, 20, 20, NULL, 'Invitation to Fellowship', 'This connection highlights the theme of invitation to share a meal, as both passages emphasize the act of dining together. In Luke, Jesus seeks a place to eat the Passover, while in Revelation, He invites individuals to open the door for fellowship.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 12, 44, 1, 13, 13, 'upper room', 'Connection of Upper Room References', 'Both passages emphasize the ''upper room'' as a significant location for the disciples. In Luke, it is where preparations are made, while in Acts, it serves as a gathering place for the apostles.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 12, 44, 16, 14, 15, 'there make ready', 'Hospitality and Preparedness', 'This connection highlights the theme of hospitality in both passages. In Luke, the preparation of the upper room signifies a place for gathering, while Lydia''s invitation to Paul and his companions reflects a similar readiness to welcome others into her home.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 12, 43, 2, 25, 25, NULL, 'Understanding Human Nature', 'This connection highlights the theme of human understanding. In Luke, the preparation in the upper room suggests a need for awareness of circumstances, while John emphasizes Jesus'' intrinsic knowledge of human nature.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 12, 43, 21, 17, 17, 'make ready', 'Connection of Preparation and Care', 'This connection highlights the theme of preparation and care in both passages. In Luke, the instruction to ''make ready'' in the upper room parallels Peter''s call to ''Feed my sheep,'' emphasizing the importance of nurturing and readiness in the ministry.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 12, 44, 20, 8, 8, 'upper room', 'Connection of Upper Rooms', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of an upper room as a gathering place. The ''upper room'' in Luke serves as a setting for preparation, while in Acts, it is a location for assembly.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 13, 42, 19, 32, 32, NULL, 'Finding as He Said', 'Both passages emphasize the fulfillment of Jesus'' words, as the sent individuals discover things exactly as He had indicated. This connection highlights the reliability of Jesus'' instructions in both contexts.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 13, 42, 21, 33, 33, 'made ready the passover', 'Connection of Endurance and Preparation', 'Both passages emphasize the enduring nature of Jesus'' words and the preparation for the Passover. The act of making ready the Passover reflects a commitment to the enduring covenant, paralleling the assurance that Jesus'' words will not pass away.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 13, 43, 2, 5, 5, NULL, 'Obedience to Instruction', 'This connection highlights the theme of obedience in both passages. In Luke, the disciples follow Jesus'' instructions to prepare for Passover, while in John, Mary instructs the servants to do whatever Jesus says.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 13, 58, 11, 8, 8, 'made ready the passover', 'Faith and Obedience in Action', 'This connection highlights the theme of obedience in both passages. In Luke, the disciples obey Jesus'' instructions to prepare for Passover, while in Hebrews, Abraham obeys God''s call to go to an unknown place.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 22, 13, 43, 11, 40, 40, NULL, 'Belief and Preparation for Glory', 'This connection highlights the theme of preparation and belief. In Luke, the disciples prepare for the Passover, while in John, Jesus emphasizes belief to witness God''s glory.', 'theme', 0.3, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
